1 Introduction

This project uses the “US Accident Injury” dataset obtained from Data.gov, which is published by US Department of Labour and spans across 15 years (from 2000 to 2015). This dataset contains information on all accidents, injuries, and illnesses reported by mine operators and contractors.

3 Using R functions to explore the data

3.1 Using str() to analyze the data

str(us_data)

There are 2000 obs with 57 variables, the data frame consist of 13 integer, 39 character and 5 numeric variables. However, there are many values like “?”, “NO VALUE FOUND” and null value need to be replaced by NA. We will do data cleaning and transform for them. And some variables like “MINE_ID”, “CONTROLLER_ID”, and “OPERATOR_ID” don’t make sense to analysis because they are actually ID. We can ignore them.

4 Data cleaning and transformation

4.1 Convert some columns to better format

us_data <- within(us_data,{
  # Parsing ID
  MINE_ID <- as.factor(MINE_ID)
  
  # Parsing dates
  ACCIDENT_DT <- as.Date(ACCIDENT_DT, "%d/%m/%Y")
  ACCIDENT_DT <- factor(ACCIDENT_DT)
})
head(us_data)

4.2 Dealing with the NA in each variable

Count the NA in each variable at first.

count_na = function(df) {
    sapply(df, FUN = function(col) sum(is.na(col)) )
}
na_sum <- count_na(us_data)
NAexists = which(na_sum > 0)
na_sum[NAexists]
##   EQUIP_MODEL_NO SHIFT_BEGIN_TIME        TOT_EXPER       MINE_EXPER 
##                1                9              360              333 
##        JOB_EXPER  SCHEDULE_CHARGE    DAYS_RESTRICT        DAYS_LOST 
##              328              673              543              422 
##    CLOSED_DOC_NO 
##             1138

However, in addition to “NA”, there are many values in the table like “?”, “NO VALUE FOUND” “9999” and null value are meaningless. So before we drop the existed NA, we must convert them to NA.(Why delete “999X” in “ACCIDENT_TIME”? Because this variable means the time accident occurred(24-hour clock). But there is not “99:9X” in our clock!)

us_data <- within(us_data,{
  # Convert the "?" to NA
  UG_LOCATION[us_data$UG_LOCATION=="?"] <- NA
  UG_MINING_METHOD_CD[UG_MINING_METHOD_CD=="?"] <- NA
  UG_LOCATION_CD[UG_LOCATION_CD=="?"] <- NA
  MINING_EQUIP_CD[MINING_EQUIP_CD=="?"] <- NA
  EQUIP_MFR_CD[EQUIP_MFR_CD=="?"] <- NA
  EQUIP_MODEL_NO[EQUIP_MODEL_NO=="?"] <- NA
  OCCUPATION_CD[OCCUPATION_CD=="?"] <- NA
  ACTIVITY_CD[ACTIVITY_CD=="?"] <- NA
  INJURY_SOURCE_CD[INJURY_SOURCE_CD=="?"] <- NA
  NATURE_INJURY_CD[NATURE_INJURY_CD=="?"] <- NA
  INJ_BODY_PART_CD[INJ_BODY_PART_CD=="?"] <- NA
  
  # Convert the "NO VALUE FOUND" to NA
  ACTIVITY[ACTIVITY=="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  MINING_EQUIP[MINING_EQUIP=="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  INJURY_SOURCE[INJURY_SOURCE=="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  NATURE_INJURY[NATURE_INJURY=="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  INJ_BODY_PART[INJ_BODY_PART=="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  UG_LOCATION[UG_LOCATION=="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  UG_MINING_METHOD[UG_MINING_METHOD =="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  DEGREE_INJURY[DEGREE_INJURY =="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  EQUIP_MFR_NAME[EQUIP_MFR_NAME =="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  OCCUPATION[OCCUPATION =="NO VALUE FOUND"] <- NA
  
  # Convert the "999X" to NA in the column "ACCIDENT_TIME"
  ACCIDENT_TIME[ACCIDENT_TIME == "9996"] <- NA
  ACCIDENT_TIME[ACCIDENT_TIME == "9997"] <- NA
  ACCIDENT_TIME[ACCIDENT_TIME == "9998"] <- NA
  ACCIDENT_TIME[ACCIDENT_TIME == "9999"] <- NA
  
  # Convert the "" to NA
  CONTRACTOR_ID[CONTRACTOR_ID==""] <- NA
  EQUIP_MODEL_NO[EQUIP_MODEL_NO==""] <- NA
  TRANS_TERM[TRANS_TERM==""] <-NA
})

We can get a conclusion that the 239 customers whose “ACTIVITY_CD” values are missing also have their ACTIVITY,INJURY_SOURCE_CD,INJURY_SOURCE,OCCUPATION_CD,OCCUPATION,NATURE_INJURY_CD,NATURE_INJURY,INJ_BODY_PART_CD,INJ_BODY_PART missing — they are the same 239 people! So it is safely to remove these rows.

newdata <- us_data[!is.na(us_data$OCCUPATION_CD),]
newdata <- newdata[!is.na(newdata$ACTIVITY_CD),]

Also, some variables only have a few NAs, such as DEGREE_INJURY, SHIFT_BEGIN_TIME, ACCIDENT_TIME and TRANS_TERM. If we remove the row where NA is, we won’t reduce our data volume much. So it’s very safely to remove them.

newdata <- newdata[!is.na(us_data$DEGREE_INJURY),]
newdata <- newdata[!is.na(newdata$SHIFT_BEGIN_TIME),]
newdata <- newdata[!is.na(newdata$ACCIDENT_TIME),]
newdata <- newdata[!is.na(newdata$TRANS_TERM),]

We have known that some variables of them are numeric variable, such as TOT_EXPER, MINE_EXPER and JOB_EXPER. Also, the number of these rows with missing data is not a large proportion of the total, so we can consider to use the mean to deal with replace their NAs.

# Replace the missing values with mean
group1 <- us_data %>% 
        group_by(DEGREE_INJURY) %>% 
        summarise(TOT_EXPER = mean(TOT_EXPER, na.rm = T))
group2 <- us_data %>% 
        group_by(DEGREE_INJURY) %>% 
        summarise(MINE_EXPER = mean(MINE_EXPER, na.rm = T))
group3 <- us_data %>% 
        group_by(DEGREE_INJURY) %>% 
        summarise(JOB_EXPER = mean(JOB_EXPER, na.rm = T))
meanTOT <- mean(newdata$TOT_EXPER, na.rm=T)
newdata$TOT_EXPER <- ifelse(is.na(newdata$TOT_EXPER),meanTOT,newdata$TOT_EXPER)
meanMINE <- mean(newdata$MINE_EXPER, na.rm=T)
newdata$MINE_EXPER <- ifelse(is.na(newdata$MINE_EXPER),meanMINE,newdata$MINE_EXPER)
meanJOB <- mean(newdata$JOB_EXPER, na.rm=T)
newdata$JOB_EXPER <- ifelse(is.na(newdata$JOB_EXPER),meanJOB,newdata$JOB_EXPER)

We can see that after our data cleaning and transformation, most columns don’t have any NA. Only some variables have a large amount of NAs, such as UG_LOCATION_CD UG_LOCATION, UG_MINING_METHOD_CD, UG_MINING_METHOD, MINING_EQUIP_CD, MINING_EQUIP. However, there are really too many NAs for these variables. If we remove all of their NAs, it will seriously affect the completeness of the data set and the accuracy of the analysis of the relationships between other variables. So we need to keep them and create subsets for analysis where appropriate.

5 Visualisation and Analyzing

5.1 Analyzing the relationship between accident frequency and years

Using bar chart to count the frequency of accidents by year.

ggplot(data = newdata)+
  geom_bar(aes(x = CAL_YR,fill=factor(CAL_QTR)),position="stack") +
  ggtitle("Frequency of accident from 2000 to 2015") + xlab("YEAR") +
  project_theme

We can see that the frequency of accident in Q3 and Q4 of 2015 are not available(probably because they haven’t been updated), so we consider data from 2000 to 2014. As a whole, the frequency of accidents is decreasing year by year. There will be special cases in some years, but overall it is becoming safer.

5.2 Analyzing the relationship between accident occurrence and time or quarter

Since the system of time is 24 hours, so the range of normal values is 0 to 2400.

ggplot(data = newdata, mapping = aes(x = ACCIDENT_TIME))+
   geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins = 50, fill = "pink")+
   geom_density(color='darkred') +
   scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0, 2400))+
   ggtitle("Time the accident/injury/illness occurred (24-hour clock)") +
   project_theme
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

The histogram and density of accident occured time shows that seems to be a bi-modal distribution which reach the peak around 10am and 2pm, which also means that this time period is the most frequent period for accidents and the accident time was concentrated in the daytime. This may be because people usually stay at home in the evening, and some people also have the habit of siestas.

Use pie chart to count the frequency of accidents by quarter.

freq = table(newdata$CAL_QTR)
piepercent<- paste(round(100*freq/sum(freq), 3), "%")

pie1=pie(freq,labels = piepercent,main="Percentage of accident time in each quarter",col = rainbow(length(freq)))
legend("topright",c("Quarter 1","Quarter 2","Quarter 3","Quarter 4"),cex=1.2,fill=rainbow(length(freq)))

We can see that the frequency of accidents by quarter is very evenly.

So we can draw a conclusion that accident the probability of an accident is closely related to the time of day, but not the quarter. We should focus on the time period with high probability of accidents and take appropriate safety measures.

5.3 Analyzing the location of accident/injury/illness occurred

We can create bar charts and pie to analyze the location within a mine where the accident/injury/illness occurred and make suggestions.

p1 <- ggplot(data=newdata)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=SUBUNIT, fill=SUBUNIT), show.legend = FALSE, width =1)+
  ggtitle("Distribution of the location")+
  coord_flip()+
  project_theme
p2 <- ggplot(data=newdata, mapping=aes(x="SUBUNIT",fill=SUBUNIT))+
  geom_bar(stat="count",width=0.5,position='stack')+
  ggtitle("Percentage of the location")+
  coord_polar("y", start=0) + 
  project_theme
grid.arrange(p1,p2,nrow=1)

We can see from the chart above, the three most likely locations for accidents are underground, strip, quary,open pit and mill operation/preparation plant. Therefore, workers should be extremely careful when working in these three places, and it’s important to take some safety measures and provide rescue support at any time.

Polar coordinate plot to analyze the distribution of the injury body part.

ggplot(data=newdata)+

It seems that human body part like fingers, knee, ankle and wrist are very vulnerable to injury. Although they can recover in a short time, they can relapse easily. Also, we should focus on the back, a body part that is prone to injury and takes a long time to heal. For these vulnerable body key parts, it’s important to remind workers to focus on protecting and raising awareness.

5.5 Analyzing the relationship between experience and degree of injure

Since these are right-skewed variables, we’ll use two histograms to analyze the distribution.

p3 <- ggplot(data = newdata, mapping = aes(x = TOT_EXPER))+
        geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins = 50, fill = "pink")+
        geom_density(color='darkred') +
        ggtitle("Histogams of TOT_EXPER") + 
        project_theme
p4 <- ggplot(data = newdata, mapping = aes(x = MINE_EXPER))+
        geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins = 50, fill = "purple")+
        geom_density(color='darkred') +
        ggtitle("Histogams of MINE_EXPER") + 
        project_theme
p5 <- ggplot(data = newdata, mapping = aes(x = JOB_EXPER))+
        geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins = 50, fill = "orange")+
        geom_density(color='darkred') +
        ggtitle("Histogams of JOB_EXPER") + 
        project_theme
grid.arrange(p3,p4,p5,ncol=1)

We see that this all three plots above shows positively skewed distribution, which means any experience of the workers is not sufficient. Could the workers’ inadequate experience have led to an increase in the degree of injuries?

Now we’ll see the influence between degree injury of different experience

p6 <- ggplot(data = newdata) + 
        geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = TOT_EXPER, y = DEGREE_INJURY), fill = "pink")+
        ggtitle("TOT_EXPER")+
        project_theme
p7 <- ggplot(data = newdata) + 
        geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = MINE_EXPER, y = DEGREE_INJURY),fill = "purple")+
        ggtitle("MINE_EXPER")+
        project_theme
p8 <- ggplot(data = newdata) + 
        geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = JOB_EXPER, y = DEGREE_INJURY),fill = "orange")+
        ggtitle("JOB_EXPER")+
        project_theme
grid.arrange(p6, p7, p8, ncol=1)

By observing the above three box plots, it is obvious that the distribution is skewed to the right because the outliers are concentrated on the side of the larger value. In general, the number of the injury is not related to the degree of injury, nor is it related to the type of job, but it’s strongly related to work experience. Therefore, we suggest that more efforts should be made to train the employees whose work experience is less than 20 to enrich their work experience. And experienced employees should also be cautious, because although their probability of injury are low, if they do, the degree of injury is same.
